## Context

The LLM resolver is the only resolver in MAIBA whose output can change
between runs (web-search models read the live web; even pure LLMs
drift across model versions). The provenance lines in N1 record what
was *applied*, but not what was *considered* — the cases where the
LLM returned a low-confidence result that got routed to the review
queue, or rejected entirely.

When a fix later looks wrong ("why does this record say 2010 when the
PDF clearly says 2009?"), today the only trail is the N1 line in the
RIS. That's not enough. We want:

- The full LLM response per item (so we can re-judge the call)
- The exact cost per item (so we can reconcile with the OpenRouter
  invoice)
- The verified URL (if any) the model cited as evidence
- A timestamp (so we can correlate with model version snapshots)

This ticket adds a per-run JSONL audit log, written as a side effect
of every LLM call regardless of outcome.

## Actions

1. **`src/maiba/audit.py`** (new, ~40 lines):
   ```python
   class LLMAuditLog:
       def __init__(self, path: Path) -> None: ...
       def record(self, *, item_id: str, model: str, cost_usd: float,
                  confidence: float, verified_url: str | None,
                  accepted: bool, raw_response: dict) -> None: ...
   ```
   Append-only JSONL. One line per LLM call. Lazy file open (don't
   create the file if no LLM calls are made).

2. **`src/maiba/resolvers/llm.py`** — after every API call, regardless
   of the outcome (accepted / below threshold / malformed / budget
   stop / timeout), call `audit.record(...)`. The audit log is
   wired into the resolver via dependency injection in `__init__`.

3. **`config/maiba.yaml`** addition:
   ```yaml
   llm:
     ...
     audit_log: "logs/llm-audit-{run_id}.jsonl"
   ```
   `{run_id}` substituted at run time (UTC ISO-8601 minute precision,
   e.g. `2026-04-28T1432Z`). `logs/` gitignored.

4. **`.gitignore`** — add `logs/` entry. Audit logs MUST NOT be
   committed (they may contain bibliographic content from
   first-pages, model responses, costs).

5. **CLI override**: `--audit-log PATH` to override the config path
   (e.g. for testing or to redirect to /dev/null).

## Test (TDD red step)

```python
# tests/test_audit_log.py
import json
from pathlib import Path
from maiba.audit import LLMAuditLog


def test_audit_log_writes_one_line_per_call(tmp_path):
    log = LLMAuditLog(tmp_path / "audit.jsonl")
    log.record(item_id="a", model="x", cost_usd=0.001,
               confidence=0.9, verified_url=None,
               accepted=True, raw_response={"title": "A"})
    log.record(item_id="b", model="x", cost_usd=0.002,
               confidence=0.4, verified_url="https://example.com",
               accepted=False, raw_response={"title": "B"})
    lines = (tmp_path / "audit.jsonl").read_text().strip().splitlines()
    assert len(lines) == 2
    rec0 = json.loads(lines[0])
    assert rec0["item_id"] == "a" and rec0["accepted"] is True
    rec1 = json.loads(lines[1])
    assert rec1["verified_url"] == "https://example.com"
    assert rec1["accepted"] is False


def test_audit_log_lazy_creation(tmp_path):
    """No file is created if no calls are recorded."""
    path = tmp_path / "audit.jsonl"
    log = LLMAuditLog(path)
    # ... no record() calls
    assert not path.exists()


def test_resolver_records_to_audit_for_every_outcome(monkeypatch, tmp_path):
    """One JSONL line per LLM call: accepted, below-threshold, malformed."""
    # exercise the LLMResolver three times with three mocked responses,
    # assert three lines appear in the audit log
    ...
```

## Exit criteria

- `make test` green.
- `make lint` green.
- After a run with `--llm-fallback`, the audit log file exists at
  the configured path and contains one JSONL record per LLM call.
- `logs/` directory is gitignored — audit logs never enter git.
- `grep accepted=false logs/llm-audit-*.jsonl` is a viable workflow
  for finding the cases that fell to the review queue.

## Out of scope

- **Long-term retention / log rotation.** The user owns the `logs/`
  directory. They can `find logs/ -mtime +30 -delete` if they want.
- **Structured search / SQLite indexing.** JSONL is plain text,
  greppable. No database until that proves insufficient.
- **PII / privacy review.** First-page text and bibliographic
  metadata can include personal names. The audit log inherits the
  same exposure as the source RIS. Documented; user decision whether
  to share log files.
